Our team played pretty well in the second quarter and ended up losing 5 more IMPs on those 12 boards (34-29). That was much better than the first quarter, but we were now down 42 IMPs with only 24 boards to go. It was natural to think, "Well at least we didn't get blown out again," but thinking like that is thinking about losing. The right attitude is, "We are underdogs and we are losing, but we can beat these guys!" We could not afford to be realistic.

Nick Gartaganis, our captain, made a smart decision when he chose to sit Joey and I out for the 3rd quarter. On the first board Canada lost 10 IMPs and the margin stood at 52 IMPs. During the remaining 11 boards, however, Canada did not lose another IMP and we scored 34 IMPs at the same time. All of a sudden we were in the match again. Italy's lead was down to just 18 IMPs and there were still 12 boards to play!

Nick now had a tough decision to make. The rest of the team had done very well without Joey and me and there was a strong case to be made for sitting us out again. Nick eventually chose to play Joey and me along with Keith and Gord while he and Peter sat out. I believe that Nick reasoned that having his most experienced pair playing at crunch time was more important than what just happened in the previous quarter. I was very happy that I would get a chance to play the last quarter, but I certainly would have respected Nick's decision had he chose to sit me out again.

It turns out that the WBF's deal generation software did an amazing job when it created the 12 boards for the fourth quarter. Almost every one of the these deals was exciting and contained scope for large numbers of IMPs to be swung. As you will see, Joey and I had a ^*Blot^*N of big hands in our direction. I am going to show you all 12 of these deals now, but I won't include too much in the way of details or analysis on most of these.
