We compared our results and added up the scores, Canada had defeated Italy by 11 IMPs! Of course, all of the Canadian players and our supporters in Salt Lake City were thrilled by our dramatic come-from-behind upset of arguably the strongest bridge team in the world.

For sure we received some luck toward the end of this match, but luck had gone against us in the first 2 quarters (the 2 huge swings to Italy that depended on the position of the @DQ, for example). But our win did not feel like a fluke - it felt like Canada had deserved to win. We had held the Italians to just 5(!) IMPs over the last 23 boards of the match. All 3 of our partnerships played a key role in Canada's victory. Italy was certainly a better team than Canada, but on this particular day it felt like nobody was going to beat us.

We only needed one more day like that. Things would not get any easier for us on that day. In the final we would face another team, Poland, that is also arguably the strongest bridge team in the world (I prefer to avoid getting into these sorts of arguments -- all of these guys are ^*Bgood^*N). Poland had come from behind in the 4th quarter to defeat Norway 112 IMPs to 89 in the other semi-final match.

Whatever happened against Poland, all of the Canadian players knew that the 2002 IOC Grand Prix would represent a high point in their bridge careers. The Poles were heavy favorites to defeat our team and the pressure was all on them. We had nothing to lose.

